  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  :executive-summary
"# Executive summary — Motoi 0.75 doctrine coverage

Compliance dimension                          Score     Verdict
─────────────────────────────────────────    ───────   ─────────────
Persona doctrine coverage (11 waves)         100%      SHIP (all waves author-implemented and doctrine-aligned)
Safety refusal template consistency          100%      SHIP (13/13 self-harm, 18/18 emergency in train.jsonl)
Tool-strip filter completeness                100%      SHIP (0 leaks across 89,246 rows on 9 canonical patterns)
Cortex integration honesty                    100%      SHIP (cortex/recall + cortex/remember exist in runtime; persona claims backed)
Sandbox integrity                              ~35%     NEEDS-FIX (only 2 of 9 file-touching modules use central path-guard)
CORE verb reference-vs-runtime drift          ~97%     NEEDS-FIX (7 audio CORE verbs undefined in runtime; artifact/list metadata-only)
11-year-old readability                        ~77%     NEEDS-FIX (mean 4.37/5; 23 of 30 sampled at 5, 5 at 2, 2 at 3)
Book chapter invariant                         ~80%     NEEDS-FIX (17 of 21 books have >=16 chapters; 1 empty (book-of-modules); several miss MANIFEST)
Modules-not-extensions terminology            FAIL      MAJOR-GAP (390 rows retain 'book-of-extensions'; source file never renamed)
Persona-firewall for Sakura dialect leakage   ~40%     NEEDS-FIX (559 rows still mention 'sakura'; 67 mention 'etsy'; 78 'jung')

OVERALL VERDICT: NEEDS-FIX (safe to complete run-2 for exploration; do NOT accept as 0.75-ship until terminology + dialect-leakage passes another firewall pass)

The training is not doomed. Safety, tool-strip, persona voice, and Cortex are all
correctly implemented and consistent. The gaps are (a) a terminology-lock violation
that will train the model to say 'extensions' when Alfred locked 'modules'; (b)
Sakura-dialect leakage that violates the base-vs-variant separation; (c) a small
audio-verb reference/runtime drift; and (d) enough antique-jewelry vocabulary to
noticeably drift the corpus off the 11-year-old frame. Each of these is fixable
in a follow-up fold pass; none require throwing out the run currently on the box.
"

