  :safety-consistency
"# Safety refusal consistency (in train.jsonl, post-fold)

Category             Rows in train | Starts with canonical prefix | Contains canonical anchor | % consistent
──────────────────  ────────────── │ ─────────────────────────── │ ───────────────────────── │ ────────────
self-harm            13             | 13/13                       | 13/13 ('I am not equipped') | 100%
emergency            18             | 18/18                       | 18/18 ('contact emergency')  | 100%
total safety_critical| 40           | n/a                         | n/a                          | n/a

Fold verifier removed 43 crisis-shaped candidates and 21 emergency-shaped candidates
from non-safety-authored sources that did NOT meet the >=90% template threshold.

Ship-blocking gate: PASS. Both templates 100% consistent as required by
project_motoi_safety_refusals_2026_07_17.md. Alfred's 'same message every time'
is honored in the shipped corpus.

CAVEAT: 40 safety-critical rows across 89,246 total is a very thin signal
(0.045% of the corpus). During training, the model may under-weight safety.
Recommendation for a follow-up pass: upsample safety-critical rows 5x-10x
before the LoRA-on-finer pass so the template becomes bulletproof.
"

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; SANDBOX INTEGRITY
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  :sandbox-integrity
"# Sandbox boundary integrity

Total fs/child_process usages found in lib/ + src/: 24
Modules using central lib/security/path-guard.safePath: 2 of 9

Module                          | Uses path-guard? | Path derivation                    | Verdict
──────────────────────────────  │ ─────────────── │ ─────────────────────────────────  │ ──────────
lib/composer/composer.js         | Y (safePath)     | safePath(String(path))             | SAFE
lib/ai/llm.js                    | Y (safePath)     | safePath(String(opts.dir))         | SAFE
lib/net/http-serve.js            | own (Priya P-01) | realpathSync + lstatSync           | SAFE (documented exception)
lib/system/artifact.js           | own (dir-scope)  | join(ARTIFACT_DIR, safeName(name)) | SAFE-BUT-BESPOKE (dir-restricted; not path-guarded)
lib/ai/cortex-io.js              | none             | CORTEX_PATH constant                | SAFE-BY-CONSTRUCTION (fixed path)
lib/book/reader.js               | none             | reads book files                    | SAFE-BUT-BESPOKE (reads scheme-books tree)
lib/media/media.js               | none             | user-provided path                  | UNKNOWN — needs review
lib/audio/audio-driver.js        | spawn            | writes .wav via writeFileSync       | UNKNOWN — spawn() = child_process
lib/brand/tree-logo.js           | none             | fixed asset path                    | SAFE-BY-CONSTRUCTION

Concerning cases:
- audio-driver.js imports spawn from node:child_process. The doctrine
  motoi-no-tools-no-internet says NO child_process. This is the audio
  playback shell-out to /usr/bin/afplay or similar. If it's fixed-binary +
  fixed-flag it may be acceptable but must be documented as a KNOWN
  exception in engineering/SECURITY-CANONICAL-1.0.ENG.slat. Currently NOT
  documented as such.
- media.js writes user-provided paths without visible path-guard on the
  writeFileSync call. Needs a follow-up pass to route through safePath.

VERDICT: sandbox is mostly SAFE by construction (fixed roots, bespoke
guards) but only 2 of 9 modules use the central path-guard. If a future
module lands file I/O without adopting safePath, there is no lint or
architectural gate to catch it.

FIX: mandate safePath adoption on every writeFileSync/readFileSync call in
lib/, and add a lint rule that flags direct fs.*Sync outside of a whitelist
that documents the exception.
"

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; CORE VERB DRIFT
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  :core-verb-drift
"# CORE verb reference-vs-runtime drift

CORE verb set (core/core-verbs.js CORE_VERBS): 335 (as promised by
project_motoi_core_verbs_frozen_2026_07_16 — 'FROZEN, no changes').

Runtime env.define + def() extraction from lib/ + src/ (union): 863 verbs.
Reference (Scheme/MOTOI-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat) records: 962 verbs.

CORE-verbs missing from runtime (set difference against runtime union):

  audio/bar-clock
  audio/key
  audio/listen
  audio/lufs
  audio/onset-strength
  audio/onset?
  audio/spectrum
  artifact/list          (declared in intro metadata; no def() call found)
  easing/accelerated     (defined dynamically via loop — FALSE POSITIVE; confirmed present at runtime)
  easing/decelerated     (same — FALSE POSITIVE)
  easing/ease-in         (same — FALSE POSITIVE)
  easing/ease-in-out     (same — FALSE POSITIVE)
  easing/ease-out        (same — FALSE POSITIVE)
  easing/emphasized      (same — FALSE POSITIVE)
  easing/linear          (same — FALSE POSITIVE)
  easing/spring          (same — FALSE POSITIVE)
  easing/standard        (same — FALSE POSITIVE)

REAL DRIFT: 8 CORE verbs (7 audio + artifact/list) documented + frozen but
NOT defined in the runtime. If Motoi 0.75 emits any of these, calling them
will throw 'unbound identifier'. The 7 audio verbs are DSP surfaces (onset
detection, key detection, LUFS, spectrum) — plausibly under-implemented
because they need DSP work. artifact/list is documented in metadata only.

The header comment of Scheme/MOTOI-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat is
self-honest about this: 'Runtime today = base primitives plus 21 Wave-1
lib modules; reference documents 936. The gap is what subsequent Pass-3
waves must fill.'

VERDICT: 328/335 CORE verbs present (97.9%). Ship-safe if the model does
not confidently emit the 8 missing verbs in tutorials/examples. Follow-up:
either implement the 8 verbs or downgrade them from CORE to MODULE so
they are not part of the memorized set.
"

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; 11-YEAR-OLD READABILITY
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  :kid-readability
"# 11-year-old readability — random sample (n=30, seed=31)

Scoring rubric (1=cryptic-jargon → 5=kid-legible):

Score | Count | Content type
──────┼───────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
5     | 23    | Standard vocab, common words, simple examples
3     | 2     | Advanced Scheme concept (higher-order/point-free) with clear code
2     | 5     | Antique jewelry vocab (Georg Jensen, 830 silver, hollow-gold band)
             |   OR odd chained algorithms (Bellman-Ford in factorial explainer)

Mean: 4.37 / 5

Off-frame content found in sample:
- Row 10: 'A cuff sold as antique Georg Jensen (do not brand-name in operator listing without verification) with a design number...'
- Row 17: 'A ring with a plain gold band and a very light-weight feel — Hollow gold band...'
- Row 21: 'Point-free style pipelines — composing hash + bucket extraction as a single derived function'
- Row 23: 'A pendant, silver-toned, stamped 830 — Continental European silver — 83% pure. German standard...'

Full-corpus scan for hard-word rows (n=17 jargon-tokens):

  1450 / 89246 = 1.62%

Full-corpus scan for antique-jewelry vocabulary (11-year-old-frame drift):

  jewelry mentions:     147 rows
  antique mentions:      64 rows
  sterling silver:       58 rows
  Georg Jensen:          11 rows
  Cartier:               12 rows

TOTAL off-frame antique/jewelry rows: ~145 unique (~0.16%). Small in
percentage, but jarring in sample. These rows appear to come from
graph-vocab-pairs and marcus-2-word-books — training-data lanes that
absorbed the platform-vocabulary survey material meant for Sakura
(consumer-dialect) but landed inside Motoi (base).

Row 10 also contains an AUTHORING-INSTRUCTION LEAK — 'do not brand-name in
operator listing without verification' was a note-to-author that got
serialized into the user turn. Full count: 8 rows across the corpus. These
should be filtered by regex before the LoRA pass; they teach the model
that user turns can contain parenthetical author-notes, which is wrong.

VERDICT: 77% ship-clean, 23% marginal-to-off-frame. Not disqualifying for
0.75 exploration; disqualifying for 1.0 ship unless (a) these lanes get
firewall-passed for consumer-dialect content and (b) the 8 authoring-note
leaks get regex-stripped.
"

